    "title": "Which Loan Apps Don't Report to CRB in Kenya?",
    "content": "<p><strong>Quick answer:</strong> There is no reliable list of loan apps that do not report to CRB, and looking for one is the wrong goal. Under Kenya's Digital Credit Providers Regulations, a licensed digital lender cannot negatively list you for an outstanding balance of KES 1,000 or less, and must give you notice before reporting. Licensed lenders generally do report, and only licensed lenders are allowed to. The government Hustler Fund has not listed defaulters, and repaying on time keeps your record clean whichever app you use.</p> <h2>Why this is the wrong question</h2> <p>Since the Central Bank of Kenya brought digital lenders under its Digital Credit Providers framework, licensed apps report borrower information, both positive and negative, to the bureaus. That comes with being regulated, not a loophole. Apps that genuinely do not report are usually unlicensed, and those carry far bigger risks: aggressive collection, contact-list harassment and misuse of your data. Choosing a lender because it might not report trades a small short-term worry for a much larger one.</p> <h2>The protections that actually exist</h2> <ul> <li><strong>The KES 1,000 rule.</strong> Under the Digital Credit Providers Regulations, a licensed digital lender may not submit negative CRB information where the outstanding amount is KES 1,000 or less. So a small unpaid balance with a licensed app should not negatively list you. This rule is specific to licensed digital lenders, not automatically every bank or SACCO.</li> <li><strong>You must be warned first.</strong> A digital lender must notify you before submitting negative information to a bureau, normally giving at least 30 days.</li> <li><strong>Only licensed lenders can report.</strong> An unlicensed app has no legitimate route to the bureaus, but it also should not be lending to you. Check whether an app is licensed, which our guide on <a href=\"/blog/how-to-check-whether-your-favorite-loan-app-is-licensed-by-the-central-bank-of-kenya\">checking a loan app licence</a> covers.</li> <li><strong>Hustler Fund.</strong> The government Hustler Fund has not listed defaulters on CRB, though it restricts further borrowing until you repay.</li> </ul> <h2>What a CRB listing really does</h2> <p>A negative CRB listing is not a permanent blacklist. It records that you defaulted, and it clears once you settle the debt and the lender updates the bureau, as our guide to <a href=\"/blog/how-do-i-clear-my-name-from-crb-in-kenya\">clearing your name from CRB</a> explains. A clean repayment history actually helps you, because it builds the record that earns bigger limits and cheaper credit later.</p> <h2>The safer approach</h2> <p>Borrow only what you can repay, from a CBK-licensed lender, and clear it on time. That protects your record far more reliably than hunting for an app that might not report, and it keeps you away from the unlicensed lenders where the real harm tends to happen. If money is tight, ask the lender for a repayment plan before the loan defaults.</p> <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2> <h3>Which loan apps do not report to CRB?</h3> <p>There is no dependable list, and apps that do not report are usually unlicensed and riskier. Licensed digital lenders generally do report under CBK rules, but they cannot list a balance of KES 1,000 or less.</p> <h3>Will a small loan default put me on CRB?</h3> <p>Not for KES 1,000 or less with a licensed digital lender, which the regulations protect. Larger balances can be listed, but only after the lender gives you notice.</p> <h3>Is being listed on CRB permanent?</h3> <p>No. It clears once you settle the debt and the lender updates the bureau. A settled entry shows as paid rather than as an unpaid default.</p> <h3>How do I protect my credit record?</h3> <p>Borrow only from licensed lenders, take only what you can repay, and clear loans on time. If you cannot pay, ask for a repayment plan before the loan defaults.</p>",
    "excerpt": "There is no reliable list of apps that do not report to CRB. Under Kenya's rules, a licensed digital lender cannot negatively list a balance of KES 1,000 or less, and must warn you first. Non-reporting apps are usually unlicensed and risky; repaying on time keeps your record clean.",
