    "title": "School fees loans in Kenya and whether bank loans beat digital lenders",
    "content": "<p><strong>Quick answer:</strong> For school fees in Kenya, the cheapest route is rarely a digital loan app. HELB serves higher-education students, banks offer longer repayment tenures that suit large termly fees, and the M-Pesa products (M-Shwari, KCB M-Pesa) suit a smaller short-term gap. The government Hustler Fund is the lowest-rate option at 8% a year but lends small amounts. Match the source to the size and timing of the fees rather than defaulting to a quick app loan.</p> <h2>The realistic options</h2> <ul> <li><strong>HELB</strong>, the Higher Education Loans Board, for university and college students, the lowest-cost route for those who qualify, repaid after studies.</li> <li><strong>Bank loans</strong> from the likes of Equity and KCB for larger termly or annual fees, with longer tenures that spread the cost, though they take longer to arrange and need documentation.</li> <li><strong>M-Pesa products</strong>, M-Shwari (one-off 9% for 30 days) and KCB M-Pesa (7.35%, about 8.82% with excise), for a smaller short-term gap close to a deadline.</li> <li><strong>Hustler Fund</strong> at 8% a year for a small top-up, with personal limits from KES 100 to KES 50,000.</li> </ul> <h2>Banks versus digital lenders</h2> <p>For a large fees bill, a bank loan usually costs less over its term and lets you repay over months, but it is slower to arrange. A digital loan is fast and convenient for a small shortfall, but it is short-term and the flat monthly fees add up if rolled over, so it is a poor fit for a big bill you cannot clear quickly. Use a bank or HELB for the bulk of fees and keep app loans for a small, last-minute gap.</p> <h2>Work out the real cost</h2> <p>Whatever you use, compare the total you will repay rather than the headline rate, with our <a href=\"/total-cost-calculator/\">total cost calculator</a>, and for the cheapest borrowing option see <a href=\"/blog/which-loan-app-has-the-lowest-interest-rate-in-kenya\">which loan app has the lowest interest rate</a>. Repay on time so a fees loan does not end in a CRB listing.</p> <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2> <h3>What is the best loan for school fees in Kenya?</h3> <p>HELB for higher education, a bank loan for large termly fees with a longer tenure, and the M-Pesa products or Hustler Fund for a small short-term gap. Match the source to the size of the bill.</p> <h3>Are bank loans better than digital lenders for school fees?</h3> <p>For a large bill, usually yes, because banks offer lower cost over a longer tenure. Digital loans suit only a small, last-minute shortfall you can repay quickly.</p> <h3>What is the cheapest way to borrow for fees?</h3> <p>HELB for those who qualify, then the Hustler Fund at 8% a year for small amounts. Compare the total repayment before choosing.</p>",
    "excerpt": "For school fees in Kenya the cheapest route is rarely a loan app: HELB for higher education, a bank loan for large termly fees with a longer tenure, and the M-Pesa products or Hustler Fund (8% a year) for a small short-term gap. Match the source to the size of the bill and compare the total repayment.",
